      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It sounds like I may have simplified a nuanced debate by implying there is only one \"correct\" answer, but the real economic consensus isn't that all domestic industries are doomed, rather that free trade generally leads to higher overall living standards in the long run. Many economists actually debate *why* industries fail (lack of innovation vs. unfair competition) and support targeted protection or training as temporary adjustments rather than permanent relying on tariffs. Ultimately, the goal isn't just accepting inefficiency, but understanding the trade-offs to design policies that balance market dynamics with social security.",
